@NODE "whatis" "What is CBAS?"

   CBAS stands for Characters Bitmaps And Sprites.  Although you may have
noticed that the word converter is attached to the end of CBAS.  This word
implies that I have atempted to make CBAS a converter rather than a file
viewer.  Although you are not forced to save out C64/128 screens as IFFs.
You may just want to view them, which you can do of course.  But I figure,
why go to all the trouble of 'porting' them, just to view them.  Not much
sense in that I think.  So, CBAS is primarily a converter and not a viewer.
That's just so some people understand why it'll be in gfx/conv on Aminet
and not in gfx/view.

CBAS allows (you) the user to perform the following:-
   
 Ě The loading of Commodore 64 Multi-Colour Bitmap and Hires images to
   view on your Amiga.

 Ě Support for 6 different Commodore 64 bitmap file formats..
   OCP Advanced Art Studio, Vidcom 64, Artist 64, Koala,Blazing Paddles,
   The Image Studio.

 Ě The viewing of upto 80 Multicolour Sprites on a single screen.  This
   will of course later be increased to however long the file containing
   sprite images is.

 Ě The viewing of upto 80 Hires Sprites on a single screen.  This will
   of course later be increased to however long the file containing
   sprite images is.

 Ě Supports Hires Character Mode and Multicolour Character Mode.

 Ě The saving out of C64 Bitmaps/Sprites as a Lores 16 Colour IFF Image.
   Therefore allowing you to load the IFF into DPaint, Brilliance,
   Photogenics etc.

   Features

 Ě Progress Pointer - When calculations are being computed a progress
   indicator guage will be displayed on screen.  This is of more use
   for users of slower machines.  Accelerated Amigas will no doubt over-
   look this feature.

 Ě Load Address Use/Ignore - In case some of your C64 files have had
   their load address 'stripped' from the file, you can use this option
   as a fallback.  It justs makes sure that the files are displayed
   correctly on-screen.  Some C64 programs append a load address on a
   file, others do not.

 Ě Clear Bitmap Data Option - Clears out any unwanted data before loading
   a new Bitmap/Sprite or Character set.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "whydid" "Why did I write it?"

   I wanted a conversion utility to import some of my C64 Graphics to
my Amiga, as I had thought about re-writing some of my old C64 games
on my Amiga.

   Just to keep the game looking like a C64 game, the graphics needed
to be converted into IFF format at first (for grabbing).  So I decided
to write a "little" program in AMOS and hey presto.

   Although the "little" program has become rather larger in size than I
had hoped, it now caters for six C64 file formats instead of just one.
I am reasonably happy with how it performs in its current state, even
more so when I added multi-colour sprite support.

   You may think an executable of some 87Żk is a rather large overhead.
You are indeed correct, it is quite appalling.  This is not a fault of
mine, more of the compiler.  The source is only 17k in length.  It's
due to some libraries installed in AMOS.  However, version 2 of this
program is currently being written, so do not despair!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "runn" "Running the program.."

 Ě Simply double-click on the program's icon from your Workbench.

 Ě Or, you can run the program from a Shell window.

 Ě ..and yes you can even place it in a Menu (Toolsdeamon) or as a
   button (Toolsmanager).

 Ě ..and yes you can install it wherever you like.

   Example usage to load a Koala file and Clear Bitmap before loading..

   Ě Press SPACE-BAR to clear the Bitmap..
   Ě Press 'F6' to select the Koala File Format..
   Ě Press 'L' to select Load File..
   Ě Select the file you want and press the OK button in the requester..

   Example usage to use Hires Sprites with no load address..

   Ě Press 'P' for Sprites..
   Ě Press 'M' to select Hires..
   Ě Press 'A' for no load address..
   Ě Press 'L' to select Load File..
   Ě Select the file you want and press the OK button in the requester..

   Its as easy as that in use, just have a mess - you won't crash the
system.  Have fun..

@ENDNODE

@NODE "progopts" "Program options.."

   There are several options currently available in this release.  They
are invoked by use of the keyboard.

       L - Load Commodore 64/128 file and display it.
       S - Save a Commodore 64/128 screen as a Lores 16 Colour IFF image.

       A - Load Address Offset (toggle - use/ignore)

       M - Switch viewing mode between Lores(160x200) & Hires(320x200).
       P - Switch viewing mode into 64/128 Sprites.
       C - Switch viewing mode into 64/128 Characters.
      F1 - Switch viewing mode into OCP File Format.
      F2 - Switch viewing mode into Vidcom 64 File Format.
      F3 - Switch viewing mode into Image System File Format.
      F4 - Switch viewing mode into Artist 64 File Format.
      F5 - Switch viewing mode into Blazing Paddles File Format.
      F6 - Switch viewing mode into Koala File Format.

   SPACE - Clear Bitmap data.

       Q - Quit the program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "fformats" "About the file formats.."

   There are at present six different file formats supported in this
program, which are:-

      * OCP Advanced Art Studio  ę Rainbird Software
      * Vidcom 64                ę Idea ?
      * The Image System         ę ???
      * Artist 64                ę ???
      * Blazing Paddles          ę ???
      * Koala                    ę ???

   All the above programs have their Copyrights still intact and will
be for some 70 years after their authors deaths.  I assume the file
formats for each program are also Copyright too.  However, I have seen
many programs in the Public Domain and Shareware libraries which display
C64 graphics files.

   So if people are making money out of these file formats under the
Shareware label, I figure that the authors will not bother about this
program as it is FREEWARE and I ain't getting any money for it - 'nuff
said !!!

   By the way, if you are an author of one of the above programs and
have a comment to make about this program (good or bad) get in touch.

   Your C64 pictures must be saved out in one of these formats before
transfering to the Amiga for use.  I used the Action Replay V cartridge
on my C64 for doing this.

   All OCP files have the MPIC extension as the last four characters
of their 16 character filename.  This is normal although you need not
keep them as this on the Amiga.  It is only for use on the C64/128
machines.

   Other C64 art programs attach other characters to the front of
filenames.  One file format attaches an inversed 'A' which on the Amiga
turns out to be a 'Special Character'.

   On programs like 64-2-Amiga used in A64 v2.0, the program cannot
handle 'Special' characters in file names.  Therefore you will have to
rename the file before transfering to the Amiga.  In addition, the '/'
'#' and '?' are not to be used as the Amiga uses these chars for
directory/file handling.

   Inserted Characters from C64 Art Packages are as follows..

      ms.  -  The Image System..
      p-   -  Artist 64..
      pi   -  Blazing Paddles..
      MPIC -  OCP (Advanced) Art Studio..
      b    -  Vidcom 64..
           -  Koala..  (I don't think Koala inserts anything.)

@ENDNODE

