@NODE "loadadd" "Load addresses.."

   When using an art package on the C64, saved out files will usually
contain a load address.  The load address is used so that the Commodore
computers know exactly where in memory to load the data that follows in
the file.  Load addresses are contained in the first two bytes of any
saved out file.  These two bytes will be in reverse order Lo-byte 
Hi-byte format.  For example..

   Typical graphics file..

      $0000  00 40 C5 C5 C5 C5 C5 C5 C5 30 30 40 55 55 6C 6C
      $00xx   ^^^   ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
              |||   |||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||
              |||   +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--- Data
              |||
              +++--- Load Address $4000

   In the above example we can see that the data following the load
address will be loaded directly into the address $4000 on a C64/C128
computer.

   CBAS now contains a `toggle' switch for Load Addresses.  You can skip
over them if they appear to be included in a file, or you can specify if
a file does not contain them.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "workami" "Compatability.."

 Ě This program should work on any Amiga previously released, as for
   new Amigas (RISC based???) I cannot make any guarantees.  CBAS
   should work fine for CDTV & CD│▓ users, if you have a keyboard!

 Ě Any Kickstart version should be fine although I cannot make any
   guarantees below KS1.3. ie. old A500s and A1000 users.

 Ě Any 680x0 Processor should be fine in use aswell.  If you've got a
   68040/68060 it should be erm, bloody fast, or instantaneous.

 Ě Caches may need to be disabled, although on my mates 50MHz 030 A1200
   everything worked fine (and fast!).

