   a pile of lard, but I ain't got the Pro Compiler (yet).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "speed" "Speed of CBAS.."

   Having written CBAS in AMOS you're probably thinking (SLOW), well,
that depends, the best method I could think of was to directly `Poke'
the data directly into the bitplanes.  This as a result was slightly
quicker than using the AMOS Plot command.  In fact having tested this
program on several systems, the results for a multicolour bitmap screen
were as follows:-

       Amiga.. RAM.............. Processors... Clock... Speed..

       A500+   2MB Chip/0Mb Fast 68000          7 Mhz   32 secs
       A500+   2Mb Chip/2Mb Fast 68010          7 MHz   28 secs
       A1200   2Mb Chip/8MB Fast 68020+68881   14 MHz   18 secs
       A1200   2Mb Chip/4Mb Fast 68030         50 MHz    3 secs

   Although you may well find faster programs on Aminet sites and better
ones aswell, this version was written to do the job exactly as it is and
not for ultimate speed or to multi-task, or anything else.

   However, please send any speeds you've noted to me via e-mail and 
I'll add them to the list.  In addition tell me your 'spec' like above 
for example.  @{"(See Contacting the Author)" LINK "contax"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "other" "Other bits in the archive.."

   In this archive you should find numerous drawers with C64 graphics in
them.  The graphics are sorted into Bitmaps, Sprites and Characters.  The
files in these drawers are for you to use as you wish.

   All the Sprites apart from the file SpaceMan I drew myself and are in
multicolour mode.  Unfortunately, some are slightly corrupted.  :( I spent
an age doing hundreds of sprites, char sets, etc.. years ago.  I just hope
I've got a backup on tape somewhere.  I think that this proves that backing
up your C64 5╝" floppies is definately recommended; and there's no better
place to store them than on your Amiga.  :)

   You will also find a program called Jibberish.AMOS in the root drawer,
where the other drawers are located.  This program was written to test my
suspicions of PlaySID v3.  I had a theory that PlaySID used the length of
a file to decide whether a C64 file is of a certain type, be it OCP,
Vidcom or whatever.  I discovered I was correct.

   The program creates a file of length equal to whichever filetype you
want and fills it with total jibberish.  The program saves out the file
to RAM: ready for you to use and test on PlaySID.  You can select what
type of C64 file you wish to save to RAM: by altering a variable in the
Jibberish.AMOS program.  I tested out the program with all six of the file 
formats that CBAS is aware of and my suspicions were indeed correct.

   You may think I'm being unfair on the coders of PlaySID.  Actually,
there is no real way of telling whether a C64 file contains jibberish or
not.  So in a way, their attempt is reasonable, however they do not deal
with Load Addresses.  I do.  So, I feel that my method is slightly better.
Auto-loading of a file is possible in a future release of CBAS, if people
want me to do it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "future" "Future versions.."

   Look out for CBAS v2.00 due to be released Summer/Autumn 1996.  New
features, time permitting:-

   KEY

   Ě DEFINATE
   Î POSSIBLE

 Î IFF to C64 - :) yes, I think some will laugh at such an idea.
   Although any 320x200x1 IFF Lores could probably done without too much
   hassle.  As for converting 320x200x4 into a 160x200 16 Colour C64
   Multicolour Bitmap, this will be tricky in the extreme.  At present,
   the only real way of dealing with this would be to ask people to
   draw their graphics in DPaint with C64 limitations ie 4 Cols per 4x8
   square, using 2 pixel wide pixels.  Other than that at present I have
   no correct and proper algorithm.

 Ě Improved Sprite viewer - I have thought of viewing sprites like the
   Action Replay V cartridge does.  Those who don't have this cartridge
   tough, I ain't goint to explain here.  Anyway this is just a thought.

 Ě Custom Palette Select - When viewing some old C64 screen, I'm sure
   most will say "Those colours aren't right!!" :)  Now listen up, the
   Amiga has some difficulty obtaining some of the C64's colours exactly
   the same way.  RGB are really difficult, so this affects the whole
   palette.  Whites on the C64 are significantly more `whiter' than on
   the Amiga.  So, you've got a "as near as dammit.." colour palette.
   In all honesty, my palette is more accurate than PlaySIDs colour
   palette (which was terrible).  Although it doesn't help when most C64
   owners had a crap TV to look at.  So all in all, its pretty damn
   close.  The next release will allow you to alter the colour palette.

 Ě Saracen Paint Bitmaps - I forgot about this one.  I found it on a
   Commodore Format covertape.  I'll look at its structure, and include 
   it in the next release.

 Ě Auto-file-detect - Load in a C64 bitmap without specifying its type.

 Î VIC-20 Bitmaps.

 Î C16/+4 Bitmaps.

 Î Simons Basic Screens?

 Î GEOS Screens?

 Î Other C64 File Formats (are there any more?)

 Ě FLI Pictures? (Those things using rasters!)

 Ě Improved Hires Bitmaps - If I recall, the C64 uses a colour map for
   Hires 320x200 screens.  My code presently treats Hires screens as all
   one colour (GREY 3).  I would like to change this for the next release.
   There is one slight snag, which is that, the Action Replay V cartridge
   can not save Hires Bitmaps.  I'm looking for some software which does.
   Are there two versions of OCP Art Studio ??? Something tells me one
   supported Hires and another Multicolour (OCP ART & ADVANCED OCP ART?).
   I'm sure someone will inform me if this is correct. Please. :)

 Ě Custom Selectable Screen Mode (Interlaced/Hires etc.)

 Ě Save Files out in other file formats. e.g
   Load in as OCP > Save out as Koala.

 Ě Complete re-write in assembler.

   If anyone has any information on any other C64 file format, I would
appreciate info on its structure.  If it could be sent to me then I
would be most grateful of your help.
   
   You may have noticed Commodore VIC-20, C16/+4 and Simon's Basic screens
aswell.  Anyway, I don't know of any VIC-20 Graphic Art Packages likewise 
for C16/+4 Art programs.

   If you do know of one, or even better know the file format structure
and have some demo bitmaps, you could mail them to me and I will include
them in the next release.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "bugs" "Bugs.."

   Having experimented with some multicolour pictures in different file
formats, I have found that there is a slight problem with a couple of the
file formats.  The problem seems to be in the $D021 colour, the reason is
down to some file formats not saving out a $D021 colour.  You may 
experience some colour changes with certain bitmaps.  For example, Vidcom,
Artist 64 and The Image System.  

   This isn't really a fault of CBAS.  PlaySID v3 has the same problem.
I'm actually glad I found this out because, it means my code is actually
okay.  So how can the problem be rectified?  In the next release you'll
be able to alter the colour palette and the bitmap should look proper.

   Apart from that I know of no bugs in CBAS.  If you think you've found
a bug let us know.  Thanks.

@ENDNODE

